On Mar 31, 2014, at 4:42 PM, &quot;Yazdanbakhsh, Arash&quot; &lt;yazdan@bu.edu&gt; wrote: 

&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;  Dear all, 
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;  This Friday, Sam Ling, from the Department of Psychological &amp; Brain Sciences at Boston University will present in our Friday journal club. 
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;  Given the classical thought that LGN does not process orientation information, it should be a very stimulating talk. Below, please find the abstract that Sam provided for us: 
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt; Title: Does the LGN process orientation information? 
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt; Abstract: Ever since Hubel &amp; Wiesel, the standard models for early vision have typically assumed that orientation selectivity first emerges in visual cortex, with little contribution from the retina and the lateral geniculate nucleus (LGN). This assumption was largely based on the idea that receptive fields the LGN and retina are concentric, and thus are incapable of coding orientation information. A growing body of empirical results, however, indicates that the notion of circular ON-OFF receptive fields may be oversimplified: receptive fields within both the LGN and the retina have been shown to have a tendency to be elongated, in a manner that would support orientation-selective processing prior to cortex. I will provide a survey of the empirical literature examining this possibility, with the hope that this will spur discussion as to whether this has any ramifications for current models of visual processing. 
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;  Hope to see you all. 
&gt;&gt;&gt;  Arash 
