On Feb 10, 2014, at 11:11 PM, &quot;Yazdanbakhsh, Arash&quot; &lt;yazdan@bu.edu&gt; wrote: 

&gt;  Dear all, 
&gt; 
&gt;  This week, our Friday JC, hosts Kyle, who will present his research on discrete prolate spheroidal sequences (DPSSs). 
&gt; 
&gt;  Below please find Kyle’s abstract for his talk: 
&gt; 
&gt; The discrete prolate spheroidal sequences (DPSSs) are a set of pair-wise orthogonal sequences, each of which is optimally signal-energy-concentrated within a specified frequency interval. They have recently been suggested as system stimuli for the purpose of determining input-output connections for a class of nonlinear, multiple-in, multiple-out (MIMO) systems (Lepage &amp; Ching, submitted, 2014). 
&gt; 
&gt; Following a review of the properties of the discrete prolate spheroidal sequences (DPSSs), I will motivate their use for system identification. The discussion will consist of simple examples and intuitive arguments. Time permitting I will present results bounding system identification performance in terms of the number of system inputs, the DPSS bandwidth parameter, the energy concentrations of the input DPSSs and system specific quantities derived from the generalized, frequency-domain system response. 
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt;  Highly recommended; hope to see you all. 
&gt;  Best wishes, 
&gt;  Arash 
